text:
Sebuah tamparan besar bagi dunia investasi digital.
Bukan sekadar grafik merah, tapi luka mental bagi jutaan orang yang terjebak euforia tanpa kendali.
Crash ini nyata, bukan hoax.
Dalam satu hari, pasar kripto terjun bebas — ratusan miliar dolar lenyap.
Bukan hanya karena sistem rusak, tapi karena keserakahan manusia yang mempermainkan angka tanpa dasar.
Kebijakan politik ikut memperkeruh suasana.
Pernyataan keras dari Trump soal tarif dan ekonomi global memicu kepanikan.
Whale melepas aset besar, leverage tinggi meledak, dan jutaan posisi terlikuidasi.
Yang tersisa hanya kepanikan, tangis, dan layar merah menyala di seluruh dunia.
Beberapa orang bahkan kehilangan nyawa — bukan karena kriptonya,
tapi karena tekanan dan keputusasaan yang mereka ciptakan sendiri.
Inilah sisi gelap pasar bebas tanpa kendali moral.
Yang jatuh sebenarnya bukan kripto,
tapi keserakahan manusia.
Pasar tidak kejam — manusialah yang tamak dan buta arah.
Jangan main leverage kalau tidak paham risikonya.
Jangan percaya influencer yang hidup dari referral, bukan dari hasil nyata.
Dan jangan pernah taruh semua harapanmu di pasar yang bergerak tanpa hati.
Belajar dari crash ini:
uang bisa hilang, tapi akal sehat jangan ikut lenyap.
Yang kita butuh bukan keberanian spekulatif,
tapi disiplin, logika, dan kerendahan hati untuk tahu kapan berhenti.
Crypto bukan musuh.
Yang berbahaya adalah manusia yang tak bisa mengendalikan diri.
Karena pada akhirnya, yang membuat rugi bukan pasar,
tapi keserakahan yang disembah diam-diam.
🕊️ Belajar dari 10 Oktober — bukan untuk takut, tapi untuk sadar...😢😢😢😢

text:
I will never use leverage again. 


This kind of manipulation by large industry players is exactly what's destroying trust in crypto.

People getting completely wrecked on 2x or 3x positions in a matter of hours isn’t just volatility — it’s engineered chaos. We’re watching massive amounts of capital being moved behind the scenes, pumping and dumping prices while regular traders get liquidated.

This isn't innovation. It's exploitation.

When billion-dollar firms manipulate markets like this, it proves the critics right — the ones who say crypto is just a scam or a rigged casino. And that’s the real damage: not just to portfolios, but to the credibility of the entire space.

Crypto was supposed to be a decentralized alternative to corrupt systems — not a playground for the same bad actors in new clothes. Until this kind of manipulation is called out and dealt with, real adoption and long-term growth are going to stay out of reach.

We deserve better.

Wars, sanctions, and global tension can shake markets overnight and central banks can’t always adapt fast enough. That’s exactly why I’ve been investing in crypto. It’s decentralized, global, and doesn’t depend on the decisions of governments or banks under pressure. I’ve grown my portfolio from $100K to $885K in just a few months by following a clear, long-term strategy with Ania Graham guidance. In times like this, crypto isn’t just a hedge it’s financial independence.

text:
It is reasonable for the U.S. to use tariffs to encourage the return of manufacturing and to keep advanced technologies within the country. However, taking actions aimed at damaging China's economy and industries—especially when they do nothing to help the U.S. economy or manufacturing—is not right.
For instance, charging special fees on Chinese-built ships may only benefit Japanese and South Korean shipbuilders, without helping U.S. ship makers . Similarly, imposing extra tariffs often just forces manufacturing to move from China to other countries, rather than bringing it back to the U.S. .
When all these actions treat China as a real enemy, it should be no surprise or doubt that China will respond with similar measures.

text:
I believe that, the CCP actually is appreciated US being number one in the world and staying well for the world stability and prosperity, even they politically cannot openly acknowledge that.
It is reasonable for the U.S. to use tariffs to encourage the return of manufacturing and to keep advanced technologies within the country. However, taking actions aimed at damaging China's economy and industries—especially when they do nothing to help the U.S. economy or manufacturing—is not right.
For instance, charging special fees on Chinese-built ships may only benefit Japanese and South Korean shipbuilders, without helping U.S. ship makers . Similarly, imposing extra tariffs often just forces manufacturing to move from China to other countries, rather than bringing it back to the U.S. .
When all these actions treat China as a real enemy, it should be no surprise or doubt that China will respond with similar measures.

Just as in the Mafia loyalty outweighs legality, in this system personal allegiance would become the highest virtue, and the law would turn into a hollow formality. text:
Do crypto investors even understand how leverage traders jeopardize the entire market with their trades? Some of these greedy folks had millions in crypto and they went into leverage trading with them. Millions. 

Just in case you don't know, if these guys don't get flushed out and the market begins to rip and they start taking profit, leverage traders alone will prematurely crash and end the bull market cycle. Let that sink in. The institutions can't let that happen. 

So I have no sympathy for leverage traders. If you have millions in crypto, you already won. But too much money is not enough money for many of these big accounts. They want to drain all the liquidity in the market and leave the rest of us holding the bag. 

Have no sympathy for them. They are a threat to your investments. People with accounts worth $10m took 10x trades. Some took 20x trades or more. Just one person. No thank you. I would rather worry about just the institutions than both institutions and leverage traders. At least institutions play the long game and won't be selling their BTC and eth every five seconds

Tapi saat ini, ya kita tau lah ada contoh kasus, ada admin yg "fraud", ada yg "memainkan pasar", dan banyak investor yg jatuh tergiur, rugi jutaan dan yg udah kecanduan jadi "gambler".

Saran saya sih ya kalau mau invest mending ke usaha yg udah jelas prospeknya, walau agak ribet sih. Kalau gak ya mending beli tanah, itu kalau pengen invest yg menguntungkan/menghasilkan. Kalau invest untuk pelindung nilai (buat tabungan/uang darurat) yg bisa lebih cepat cair mending beli logam mulia seperti emas, perak dll. Walau sistem harga juga pakai "supply & demand, logam mulia relatif lebih stabil dan tiap tahun biasanya naik. Ini karena logam mulia gak cuma dibeli sebagai alat investasi, ini bisa jadi bahan baku perhiasan, alat elektronik, dll jadi permintaan pasar lebih stabil & aman.

Recession Signals – Crypto Outlook (Q4 2025 - 2026)

False info. If you get liquidated on a leveraged position/account you don't _just_ lose the small amount of collateral, even without cross margining. When you are 10x leveraged and btc drops 10% you lose just about *everything* . The only thing is that the drop your position can stomach before liquidation gets smaller the more cross margin you do.

TL;DR Play big games, win big (negative) prizes.

text:
Bizarre assertation/analysis (to be kind).  The fact that a company holds BTC doesn't make it a BTC treasury company any more than holding cash on its balance sheet makes it a central bank.
The vast majority of individuals (and companies) who hold BTC on their balance sheet do it (and many many many more will continue to do it) because it's a somewhat uncorrelated asset that both has established market acceptance and cannot be created ad hoc. Thus it holds or increases its value (on average) against inflation.
Some other cryptos though not being as strict in the inability to create more have a mechanism (staking) to also provide a positive return.  Which also makes them a viable asset class.
While it's true that the crypto treasury company phenomenon is providing additional demand currently.  Even if that unwinds, the fundamental viability/long-term benefits of having BTC or other crypto on a company's balance sheet in some amount doesn't go away.

text:
Singular "be" verbs (like is, am, was) are used with singular subjects, while plural "be" verbs (like are, were) are used with plural subjects. The verb form depends on the number of the subject: for example, "The result is significant" (singular) vs. "The results are significant" (plural). The verb "be" is particularly irregular, so its singular and plural forms (am, is, are, was, were) must be learned separately for each pronoun. 
Singular "be" verbs

    is: "The dog is happy." / "He is a student."
    am: "I am hungry."
    was: "She was tired." 

Plural "be" verbs

    are: "The dogs are happy." / "They are students."
    were: "We were tired."
    be: "You be careful." (This is less common in everyday conversation, but is often used in imperative sentences and some dialects.) 

Irregularities and special cases

    You: This pronoun is a special case because it can be both singular and plural, but it always takes a plural verb form: "You are happy" (whether you are talking to one person or many). 

Third-person plural: "They" always takes a plural verb form: "They are coming over." 
First-person singular: "I" takes the unique singular verb form "am": "I am going to the store."

text:
Mark Moss shouldn’t be taken as a fully reliable forecaster:

No verified track record — He doesn’t publish timestamped results comparing predictions vs. outcomes.

Constantly shifts timelines — When crashes or “resets” don’t happen, he moves the goalposts forward.

Extreme narratives — Uses attention-grabbing phrases (“everything bubble,” “reset,” “collapse”) that drive clicks more than accuracy.

Conflicting messages — Sometimes warns of imminent crashes, other times claims “no crash coming.”

Monetary bias — He’s a Bitcoin maximalist; every macro story leads back to “buy BTC,” which skews analysis.

No institutional accountability — Unlike licensed analysts, he’s not bound by compliance or fiduciary standards.

Profit incentive — Fear-based content generates YouTube revenue and product sales, rewarding exaggeration.

text:
Ancient Greece & Rome: Thinkers like Aristotle warned that if the wealthy dominate politics, they’ll pass laws in their own interest instead of for the common good. The Romans saw this too — merchant-elite families in the Senate often pushed policies that widened inequality and destabilized the Republic.
	•	Medieval and Renaissance Europe: In Italian city-states like Florence, merchant families (like the Medici) gained control. They brought prosperity, but also corruption, nepotism, and power struggles. Historians often point to them as proof that when wealth and politics merge, democracy weakens.
	•	China: Confucian scholars distrusted merchants in politics, arguing they pursued profit over virtue. Dynasties sometimes banned merchants from holding office, fearing they’d undermine moral governance.
	•	Modern Warnings: In the U.S., the Founding Fathers worried about concentrated wealth corrupting democracy. Historians today often note how corporations and business elites funding politics can tilt government toward private gain.
